## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three compounding bugs** — any one of them is bad, but together they create a rapidly cascading leak that worsens on every navigation.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Re-adds Listeners on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array = runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
});
```

When `useEffect` has no second argument, React re-runs it **after every single render** — not just on mount. The sequence looks like this:

```
1. Component mounts          → effect runs → 2 listeners added (total: 2)
2. User scrolls              → handler fires → setState x3 → re-render
3. After re-render           → effect runs AGAIN → 2 more listeners (total: 4)
4. Next scroll fires 4 handlers → more setState → more re-renders → +2 more
5. (exponential growth)
```

State updates (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`) trigger renders, which trigger more effects, which add more listeners, which fire on the next scroll and trigger more renders. It's a self-feeding spiral.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Survive Unmount)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

`window` is a **global singleton** — event listeners attached to it are never automatically garbage collected when a React component unmounts. When the user navigates away, the component is destroyed but every listener it ever registered keeps running, holding closure references (to state setters, captured variables, the whole component scope) alive in memory.

Each navigation cycle:
```
Visit 1 → N listeners added, never removed
Visit 2 → N more added on top → 2N total
Visit 3 → 3N total, all firing
...
Visit 10 → 10N listeners all competing, burning CPU on every scroll/resize
```

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Can't Be Removed

```jsx
// ❌ These are new function objects created on every call
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });

// This would silently do NOTHING — it's a different function reference
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
```

`removeEventListener` uses **referential identity** to find which listener to detach. An arrow function defined inline creates a brand-new object every time — even two syntactically identical `() => {}` expressions are different objects in memory. Without a stable named reference, cleanup is **impossible**, even if you tried to write it.

---

## Bonus Bug #4 — `lastScrollY` as State (Unnecessary Re-renders)

`lastScrollY` never appears in the JSX — it's pure internal tracking state. Storing it with `useState` means every scroll event fires an extra re-render just to update a value the user never sees. It should be a `useRef`, which updates synchronously without triggering renders and also eliminates a stale closure risk (the ref always reflects the current value when the handler fires).

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Immediately Visible

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally double-invokes effects**:

```
Mount  → effect runs  → 2 listeners added
        → cleanup runs (but there is no cleanup!)  → listeners stay
Re-mount → effect runs AGAIN  → 2 more listeners (total: 4 on first load)
```

Without a cleanup function, Strict Mode's simulated unmount/remount cycle immediately doubles your listeners on the very first page load. This is by design — React is probing your component to reveal exactly this class of bug during development before it ships to production.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY]               = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // ✅ useRef instead of useState: internal tracking value that doesn't need
    //    to trigger a render. Always reflects the latest value in the handler
    //    without stale-closure issues.
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named functions: stable references that removeEventListener
        //    can actually locate and detach.
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY; // mutate ref, no re-render
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup function: runs on unmount (and before each re-run in
        //    Strict Mode). Removes the EXACT same function references that
        //    were registered above.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // ✅ Empty array: effect runs once on mount, cleanup runs on unmount.
            //    Handlers read live values via ref, so no deps needed here.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners added on every render | Missing `[]` dependency array | Add `[]` — run effect only on mount |
| Listeners survive unmount | No cleanup function | Return `() => removeEventListener(...)` |
| Cleanup is impossible | Anonymous arrow functions | Extract named `handleScroll` / `handleResize` |
| Unnecessary re-renders | `lastScrollY` as `useState` | Replace with `useRef` |

The corrected component adds exactly 2 listeners on mount, removes exactly those same 2 listeners on unmount, and is fully compatible with React 18 Strict Mode's double-invocation behavior.

